{"title":"My Bike: Leah Thomas’ Team Movistar Canyon","link":"https://cyclingtips.com/2021/03/my-bike-leah-thomas-team-movistar-canyon-ultimate/","date":1614623469000,"content":"<p>Welcome to another That&#8217;s My Bike. In this episode, I chat with the new Movistar signing Leah Thomas. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Joining a new team for the 2021 season brings with it not just new teammates, new challenges and a fresh start, but a new team bike and new equipment. In this case, it&#8217;s a Canyon Ultimate (she gets her Aeroroad later in the season and yes we know that&#8217;s an Aeroad in the thumbnail shot, sorry). At Movistar, the women&#8217;s team gets exactly the same setup as the men&#8217;s team, from clothing sponsors through to the equipment that the bike is decked out in.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"894\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Canyon-Aeroad-CFR-001-1340x894.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-484371\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Canyon-Aeroad-CFR-001-1340x894.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Canyon-Aeroad-CFR-001-650x434.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Canyon-Aeroad-CFR-001-190x127.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Canyon-Aeroad-CFR-001-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Canyon-Aeroad-CFR-001-16x11.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Canyon-Aeroad-CFR-001.jpg 1499w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption>Though Leah doesn&#8217;t have her Aeroad yet it will be arriving soon enough.</figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>This season Leah is back on Sram after a few years away from it. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>The bike&#8217;s running kit is, of course, SRAM&#8217;s top-end groupset, the Red AXS eTAp. Wheels are from SRAM&#8217;s sister brand Zipp. For training, she&#8217;s on the US company&#8217;s 302 wheelsets, (that even still have the old logos, what a downgrade!) These are wrapped in rubber from the long-time tyre sponsor of the Movistar team, Continental&#8217;s GP 5000. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>Finishing out the bike components are Keo Blade pedals from Look, a product Leah&#8217;s never used before but claims she&#8217;s getting on well with. And finally, keeping her comfy is a Fizik saddle &#8211; just don&#8217;t ask her what model of perch it is; she&#8217;ll learn that for the next vid I&#8217;m sure.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-002-1340x893.jpg\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-484379\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-002-1340x893.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-002-650x433.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-002-190x127.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-002-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-002-16x11.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-002.jpg 1500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption>Out getting the miles in at the 2021 Movistar Team Training Camp, AlmerÌa. </figcaption></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>Like every other video in this series, I&#8217;ve nagged the participant to film their own bike. Leah was kind enough to get the hose out and get the bike looking 100% showroom-ready. Luckily for us, Leah isn&#8217;t as rapid with her shots as Toms was in our last episode &#8211; sorry Toms to call you out, mate.</p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-columns\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-column\" style=\"flex-basis:100%\">\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<figure class=\"wp-block-gallery columns-3 is-cropped\"><ul class=\"blocks-gallery-grid\"><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1333\" height=\"1000\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_4126.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"484376\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_4126.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=484376\" class=\"wp-image-484376\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_4126.jpg 1333w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_4126-650x488.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_4126-190x143.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_4126-510x382.jpg 510w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_4126-1080x810.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_4126-16x12.jpg 16w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1333px) 100vw, 1333px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">Training wheels are from Zipp, their 302 model wrapped in Continentals very lovely 5000 tires.</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1333\" height=\"1000\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_8981.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"484374\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_8981.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=484374\" class=\"wp-image-484374\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_8981.jpg 1333w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_8981-650x488.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_8981-190x143.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_8981-510x382.jpg 510w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_8981-1080x810.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/IMG_8981-16x12.jpg 16w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1333px) 100vw, 1333px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">Leah, showing off her new chainset and Look Keo blade pedals.</figcaption></figure></li><li class=\"blocks-gallery-item\"><figure><img loading=\"lazy\" width=\"1340\" height=\"893\" src=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-020-1340x893.jpg\" alt=\"\" data-id=\"484368\" data-full-url=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-020.jpg\" data-link=\"https://cyclingtips.com/?attachment_id=484368\" class=\"wp-image-484368\" srcset=\"https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-020-1340x893.jpg 1340w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-020-650x433.jpg 650w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-020-190x127.jpg 190w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-020-1080x720.jpg 1080w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-020-16x11.jpg 16w, https://cyclingtips.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/02/2021-Almería-Camp-J-14-Wmn-020.jpg 1500w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1340px) 100vw, 1340px\" /><figcaption class=\"blocks-gallery-item__caption\">Out and about training at the team camp in early January.</figcaption></figure></li></ul></figure>\n</div></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n<p>The post <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://cyclingtips.com/2021/03/my-bike-leah-thomas-team-movistar-canyon-ultimate/\">My Bike: Leah Thomas&#8217; Team Movistar Canyon</a> appeared first on <a rel=\"nofollow\" href=\"https://cyclingtips.com\">CyclingTips</a>.</p>","author":"Dave Everett","siteTitle":"CyclingTips","siteHash":"30feca30fb3902119bf2da6559e7337232527b61c9abe0a00f5d7543c6aa6c84","entryHash":"cf5562ca9cd70dda62e5f231d1c01016d0358e01b7eab6a6072675853677f420","category":"Cycling"}